The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, June 16, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 Great Eastern Shipping Company Ltd has swapped a part of its international floating interest rate liabilities into fixed rates to insulate itself against a possible rise in interest rates. Most of the companys term-loan liabilities are dollar denominated with a floating interest rate linked to Libor. As a risk management measure, the company has used simple derivative tools to swap a part of these into fixed interest rates, GE Shipping said in its annual report for 2003-04.																								 Hindustan Zinc Ltd has posted a 184.52 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 404.6 crore in 2003-04 compared with Rs 142.2 crore in the previous year. The board has recommended a dividend of 14 per cent (Rs 1.40 per share), the company informed the Bombay Stock Exchange.																								 RBS Home Appliances, a distributor of Siemens home products in India, aims to double turnover at Rs 80 crore this year due to rising sales of washing machines and refrigerators. The company might set up a manufacturing unit in the country in three to five years, by when sales should attain a critical volume, managing director Vipul B Raval said.																								 The Automotive Component Manufacturers Association of India is taking a contingent of 28 companies to participate in the Tehran International Auto Fair from June 20 to 24. The Iranian automotive market is growing. It offers excellent business potential to many Indian firms, an ACMA release said.																								 Federal Bank has revised the interest rates of fixed deposits of NRI accounts. For pound sterling FCNR accounts of a three-year term, the maximum rate is 5.34 per cent, a bank release said. It is 3.43 per cent for dollar accounts for the same term and 2.97 per cent for euro.																								 Nirma Ltd has posted a 23.28 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 263.71 crore in 2003-04 against Rs 213.91 crore in 2002-03. The board has recommended a dividend of 40 per cent on shares for 2003-04, the company informed the Bombay Stock Exchange.																								 Mirza Tanners has reported a net profit of Rs 16.74 crore in 2003-04 compared with Rs 13.95 crore in the previous year. The companys turnover stood at Rs 188.49 crore against Rs 164.95 crore in the previous fiscal, a company release said.																								 Ion Exchange (India) Ltd, a water treatment major, has deployed an arsenic-removal technology in rural areas through community handpump attachment units. The company has supplied 150 units to the Bengal public health and engineering department for North 24 Parganas.																								 Polar Pharma India Ltd will launch Adam range of premium condoms in the eastern, northeastern and southern regions in July. It plans a national launch towards the year-end. ADVERTISEMENT
